<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-07-20T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-07-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="507" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d507">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01/7–2049: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Taipei</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Macdonald</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Taipei</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-07-20">July 20,
                                1949</date>.<lb/>[Received July 20—5:07 a. m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>300. Press carries announcement of creation of office of Generalissimo in
                            Taipei under Chief Secretary Huang Shao-ku. Five sections: <pb facs="0457" n="447" xml:id="pg_447"/> Party and political sections
                            under Ku Cheng-kang; foreign section under Wang Shih-chieh; finance
                            section under O. K. Yui; military section under General Wang Tung-yuan;
                            secretariat under Professor Chang Chi-yun.</p>
                        <p>Sent Department; repeated OffEmb Canton 130.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Macdonald</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>